# How `this` works

## Overview

A Linux sandbox that creates a throwaway user session on demand.
Every write is RAM-backed and gone on exit host filesystem is never touched.

The goal was simply to run sway under a tmp user with some things backed in.

## Launch
`sudo ./user [options]` sets up the session:
- Creates a temporary user (`tmpuser_XXXX`) with a random name
- Mounts a tmpfs-backed overlay on a fresh home dir (`/var/tmp/home_XXXX`)
- Overlays `/usr`, `/etc`, `/var/lib`, `/var/cache` in RAM (shared with broker)
- Drops into the session via `unshare` (pid/mount/uts/cgroup namespaces)
- Cleans everything up on exit (user, mounts, dirs)

## Inside the session
Starts via `session-init`, which launches any defined services then execs `bash --login`.
When bash exits the PID namespace dies, killing all background services instantly.

### Networking
- Default: host network (no isolation)
- `--no-net`: loopback only
- `--eth`: veth pair + bridge, random ULA IPv6 + RFC1918 IPv4, NAT to host

### Wayland
- `--wayland`: standalone compositor via seatd, or nested if a host socket is found
- D-Bus session bus started on host, socket forwarded into the session
- Run `sv setup sway && sv start sway` inside the session to start a compositor

### Root broker
- `--allow <cmd>`: whitelists a command the session can run as root (repeat for multiple)
- `run-as-root <cmd>` inside the session sends the command to `broker.py` over a Unix socket
- Broker nsenter's the session's own mount namespace, then unshares a fresh PID namespace with a clean `/proc`
- Commands run as root with full access to the session's live overlay — installed packages are visible immediately
- Example: `sudo ./user.sh --wayland --allow pacman --allow reflector`

## Services (sv)
`sv` manages background processes inside the session:

```
sv setup  <name> [command]  create a service (defaults to: exec <name>)
sv start  <name>            start it in the background
sv stop   <name>            stop it
sv status <name>            check if running
sv delete <name>            stop and remove the service definition
```

Services live in `$SVDIR/<name>/run`. A `down` file prevents auto-start.
Any service started at session-init time is killed automatically when the session ends.

The `--temp` flag uses an ephemeral service dir (`$SVDIR_TEMP`) that is gone when the session exits:

```
sv --temp setup <name> [command]   ephemeral service, not persisted to ~/.imut
sv --temp start  <name>
```

Persistent services (no `--temp`) live in `~/.imut/sv/` and auto-start on the next session.

## Persistent store (~/.imut)

- `~/.imut/` is bind-mounted into every session — survives exits, owned by the real user
- `~/.imut/home/` — anything here gets **symlinked** into the session `$HOME` at launch (dotfiles, configs, etc.)
- `~/.imut/history` — session shell history is symlinked to `~/.bash_history` automatically
